    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3971076599" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3971076599" />
    <a title="Jack Woods" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/124104029-jack-woods"><img alt="Jack Woods" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1617205540p2/124104029.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3971076599?book_show_action=true">May 01, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jack Woods" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jack Woods" href="/user/show/124104029-jack-woods">Jack Woods</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780062565396" href="/book/show/29938407-the-four-loves">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3971076599" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13817279663876536251">This is probably my favorite book I’ve read all year. I hadn’t read any cs lewis since I read screwtape letters last year and I was reminded just how amazing of a writer Lewis is.<br/><br/>He lays out so beautifully both the positive aspects of each of the earthly, human loves, but also describes in unnerving detail the ways in which we distort, twist and pervert these loves from what they are meant to be.<br/><br/>In describing the human love of affection, he writes “If affection is made the absolute sovereign of </span>
  <span id="freeText13817279663876536251" style="display:none">This is probably my favorite book I’ve read all year. I hadn’t read any cs lewis since I read screwtape letters last year and I was reminded just how amazing of a writer Lewis is.<br /><br />He lays out so beautifully both the positive aspects of each of the earthly, human loves, but also describes in unnerving detail the ways in which we distort, twist and pervert these loves from what they are meant to be.<br /><br />In describing the human love of affection, he writes “If affection is made the absolute sovereign of a human life the seeds will germinate. Love, having become a god, becomes a demon.” This idea, that elevating any human love to the role of god will either destroy the love or transform it into something that you never imagined it would become, is central to each of the human loves as Lewis sees them. In affection, there is the danger that rather than seeking the best for the object of their love, they long for them to never change as this threatens the love as it currently exists. In friendship, there is the temptation to isolate within one’s group and be puffed up with pride against those deemed inferior. In Eros, there can arise the reckless desire to follow the whims of a temporal feeling above devotion to children, a spouse or even God.<br /><br />However, Lewis does not stop there. The ultimate goal for any earthly love is not just that they would not become a god but rather that they would find their true beauty and complete fulfillment in a heart that is fully dependent on God.<br /><br />“Even for their own sakes the loves must submit to be second things if they are to remain the things they want to be. In this yoke lies their true freedom; they ‘are taller when they bow’.<br /><br />In all of a man’s relationships, there must be the implicit understanding that no love, no devotion, no commitment comes before his devotion to the Lord.<br /><br />“The real question is which (when the alternative comes) do you serve, or choose, or put first? To which claim does your will, in the last resort yield?<br /><br />“It is too late, when the crisis comes, to begin telling a wife or husband or mother or friend, that your love all along had a secret reservation - "under God" or "so far as a higher Love permits". They ought to have been warned; not, to be sure, explicitly, but by the implication of a thousand talks, by the principle revealed in a hundred decisions upon small matters. Indeed, a real disagreement on this issue should make itself felt early enough to prevent a marriage or a Friendship from existing at all. ... “If "All" - quite seriously all - "for love" is implicit in the Beloved's attitude, his or her love is not worth having. It is not related in the right way to Love Himself.”<br /><br />Insightful throughout, and at several points deeply convicting, this book is an absolute masterpiece.<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13817279663876536251" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


